### Description

A common template pattern today is nesting `@defer` inside `@for` for per-item lazy rendering:

```html
@for (example of examples; track example) {
  @defer (on viewport) {
    <my-component [example]="example" />
  } @placeholder {
    <div>Large component placeholder</div>
  }
}
```

This is explicit, but fairly verbose for a very common use case.

I would like to propose a shorthand syntax

### Proposed solution

```html
@for (example of examples; track example; defer on viewport) {
  <my-component [example]="example" />
}
```

```html
@for (example of examples; track example; defer on viewport) {
  <my-component [example]="example" />
} @placeholder {
  <div>Large component placeholder</div>
}
```

or

```html
@for (example of examples; track example; defer(on viewport)) {
  <my-component [example]="example" />
} @defer:placeholder {
  <div>Large component placeholder</div>
}
```

### Alternatives considered

This proposal does not require changing the runtime semantics of `@for`.

The idea is to treat it purely as syntactic sugar for an already valid and existing pattern:

```html
@for (item of items; track item; defer on viewport) {
  <my-component [item]="item" />
}
```

would be desugared by the template parser/compiler into:

```html
@for (item of items; track item) {
  @defer (on viewport) {
    <my-component [item]="item" />
  }
}
```

In other words, the shorthand would not introduce a new execution model for `@for`.
It would only provide a more compact way to express "wrap each iteration body into its own `@defer` block".

Semantically, this means:

each iteration gets its own deferred block;
existing `@defer` behavior stays unchanged;
trigger evaluation still happens per iteration;
companion blocks such as `@placeholder`, `@loading`, and `@error` would belong to the implicit per-iteration `@defer`, not to `@for` itself.

From the compiler perspective, this should be equivalent to lowering the shorthand into the already supported nested block structure before further template compilation.
That makes the feature easier to reason about, because it reuses existing `@defer` semantics instead of introducing special-case behavior into `@for`.

